{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"41fb72a7-eb68-4db2-91ca-521ce084c287","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example usage:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nFor **xUnit theories**, use `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` instead of `[Fact]`. All four frameworks will report these as skipped (not failed) in test results.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aaf32085-8ef3-424a-ade5-fabdc53207ec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":316,"requestId":"0430:207FB7:187B05D:1BC3E7B:69E81E35"},"id":"61bf9a68-b6b1-4839-895e-dbc3a3223362","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:02:51.314Z","parentId":"7018ebd3-0b5f-4346-a8b4-734bdccf5f7f"}
